The Prague Stock Exchange ended with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall of the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
Transactions in ČEZ's shares reached approximately half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of the commercial Tuesday, reacted immediately to Monday's fall when it fell to about 6%.
The drop this time is due to the fall of stocks on Wall Street.
Also here is expressed the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American Assembly of Representatives that refused to support the stabilization plan of the secretary of the financial sector.
Fall of actions in Asia
The shares of the Asian Stock Exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although throughout the day the index finally attenuated part of the losses.
Hong Kong's Hang Seng Stock Exchange index throughout its financial day stood at almost four percent, although it later attenuated its losses by reducing the decline by almost 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index that follows Chinese stock movements on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange dropped by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai markets were closed.
Sidney's stock market lost more than five percent but, in the end, losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the Secretary of the Index, fell to 3.6 percent.
"Rescue actions programmed in the U.S. are insecure and this influences the financial market around the world," said Hong Kong Currency Office Chief Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, i.e., without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong's interest rates are at the same level as those of the United States.
American legislators should reconvene as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens to make falls felt in other countries.
Bloody bath of American actions
On Monday, the American Assembly of Representatives rejected the financial system aid plan to which 700 billion dollars (almost 12 billion kroner) should be devoted.
Lawmakers, in this way, ignored President George Bush's invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would solve the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, American stocks experienced a bloody bath and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index dropped to almost seven percent. A similar volume drop was last recorded in 1987.
The index dropped before it was announced but as soon as it was shown that the assembly's proposal did not go ahead, the index began to fall freely.
Congress withdraws: U.S. government can inject $700 billion into banking
The highest representatives of Congress and the government, President George W. Bush, agreed on a pact in broad terms of financial aid to the American financial system.
Their vote will take place at the beginning of next week.
American legislators caused a gap in talks about the approval of the bailout plan in its form of aid to the American financial system with the amount of $700 billion (approximately 12 billion kroner).
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must refine some details of the contract before they can make public the final form of the law and have it voted.
The financial system support plan will be discussed Monday in the Assembly of Representatives.
He said Sunday to Reuters agency, Barney Frank, chairman of the Assembly Committee for Financial and Banking Services.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could take place in the Senate not before Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the rescue plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
Then, however, "disenchantment" will be achieved thanks to the complex mechanisms whose market support will also reach in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made a great breakthrough.
We resolved our dissenting views on the form the market stabilization package should have," Democrat Nancy Pelosiá told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still take place on Sunday.
Representatives of legislators met Sunday night with finance minister Henry Paulson to give a definitive form to the government fund.
It should buy from financial companies the unsold mortgage assets that lead financial companies to heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are about to close the agreement on the plan, which will work and will also have to be effective on the market.
The sanitation plan still needs to be continued, but I think we're already working on it," said Paulson.
A Sign for Asian Business
The global financial crisis has an explicit impact on the rapidly declining stock market.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, legislators are doing everything they can to get Congress finally to approve an agreement this Sunday.
They want to reassure investors' businesses in the Asian finance market because these are the ones in the first time zone and where Congress could influence Monday's trade.
However, for now there is nothing clear for sure about when the two chambers of American Congress will vote and even if they will not stagnate at the last moment with any problems.
Lawmakers believe it will be approved in the coming days.
The law, however, will undergo a series of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system should be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion must be available as soon as possible, as requested by President George Bush.
However, Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it had the impression that the program does not fulfill its function, which would be another $100 billion and, later, the last $350 billion.
Bush Appreciated the Progress of Meetings
On the other hand, the president may veto this decision but Congress can overcome its veto by a majority vote.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program was preserved, which consisted of earning financial resources for the repurchase of bad mortgage securities whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to finish paying their mortgages.
"We've worked everything out.
The Assembly of Representatives would have to be prepared to vote the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
American President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the meetings.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush is satisfied with Saturday's advance and values "the commitment of both sides to stabilize our financial market and protect our economy."
Limitation of the armoured contract
Senate banking committee chairman Christopher Dodd, head of negotiators, said legislators decided on the responsibility for the taxpayer's tax protection program's money for its losses, a easing closure of the scheduled finance plan.
The new law should also limit so-called armored contracts for directors of participating companies of the program, and set up a committee that will have control of the Fund.
This one would have to be run by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on it, and we have made a breakthrough in the direction of the agreement that will work and that will be effective for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also has to help homeowners who have problems with their payments.
The government would have to agree with the new mortgage payments it buys in order to lower the monthly payments charges on debtors' instalments and enable them to keep their homes.
Marek: psychological help
The proposed plan is, according to the chief economist of Homeland Finance, David Marek, a good idea that will be realized but quite difficult.
"And this is why it is not known with what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be purchased.
This will be decisive for the distribution of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week, for the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not, according to Marek, so relevant.
"Much more important is that, already this week the congressmen agree on their support and give it their approval as soon as possible.
This important and psychological agreement to get that approval is, at the moment, the most important thing," Marek insisted.
Armed fighting: the MP3 Player against the mobile phone.
We advise you how to choose
While almost all mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player gets to make calls.
Which seems clear that it's better to just buy the phone.
Yet there are sufficient grounds for man to acquire only the player.
The choice depends practically on the way of its use and the requirement of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for him to acquire the most modern record player to listen to on it Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
On the other hand this type of musical products such as LP discs no longer come out, and as far as their quality is concerned there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If vinyl records with art rock, jazz or blues are packed on their shelves, you're probably dreaming, at least, of this kind of record player.
This is the same with the music that is on the way, that is, the compressed, simplified music - the music in MP3.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a player, as well as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly test the twenty-kronor market helmets.
Two ends, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
Also decides the battery life
Some of the best players get much more than just playing music and even what not even most mobiles do.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In front of the most elementary functions such as phone, send messages, can play music and video, record both, has a better or worse photographic device and can even manage to navigate.
And when we take into consideration the Smartphone and the PDAs will also have in their pocket a small computer.
This is a small miracle as no fridge can do a barbecue and no television can photograph.
The universality of mobiles also brings us disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile before the display indicator will be illuminated by asking to be recharged.
And the reproduction of music is one of the biggest energy gulps.
Few are mobiles that can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most of them much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest) clearly have a higher performance.
Therefore, keep in mind that cheap phones will not play more than two hours.
If in addition to this, on top of it, constantly call get yourself even, for more safety, a loader for work - this is also valid for the most expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player this problem is not going to have it, because even the worst ones endure at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a load.
Another problem happens when you record music on your mobile phone.
Unfortunately only a part of the devices has the universal USB connector and, moreover, not all of them can connect directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly on the memory card but only on some unreduced reader drives can the small memory cards that are used on mobiles be connected.
In players, with some exception (iPod), no special software is required.
Simply fill the device with music via the USB computer.
Most mobiles and players create their order alone in the music library according to the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
For the choice of a specific equipment, be interested in the strength of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of its handling.
If you listen, above all, to the music as a background and you will listen to it every day just for a while, like on the tram, then it is enough with any mobile that plays.
Which practically achieves any real motive.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile phone or player plays the music.
The MP3 is played by all of them, and practically all the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
The least include the AAC format (format used by Apple company and its iPod).
The best mobiles also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough by means of the mobile internet to visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album.
This service could by itself be a weighty argument to acquire a mobile for music.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is miserable and the majority is limited only to the topics of fleeting success of the radios.
Prices aren't the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (either by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a cell phone.
Whenever you feel like hearing something, you will find your mobile phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or, at least, handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has practically every mobile even if it is at least one MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobiles with music will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can already acquire a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited to the absence of an entry for classic headphones.
The best, even as far as the technical part is concerned, such as telephones equipped with a 3.5 mm input for classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing but their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are actually handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, their handling similar to the previous current cassettes or also to the turntables is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with the mobile phone and, consequently, huge account for data loss.
Which device to decide on
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot to change the memory card (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card it will reach 2,000 crowns.
However, be careful.
The basic models are normally equipped with only a card of 2 GB maximum capacity.
Only the most expensive ones have an 8GB memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy still a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) no more than 1,100 crowns are needed.
If you consider yourself one of the most demanding music lovers take advantage of the most specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of the same player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose walkman cell phones have almost identical use as an independent MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, about the four thousand crowns, but with a greater capacity of memory (up to 16 GB) and accumulator (usually of 15 hours, with a maximum yield of up to 35 hours), the most arria brand brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will be arriving, this year, in the Czech Republic.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it in mobile.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees it is likely to come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks competition that really wants to fight.
We probably find this paradoxical, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, said that there is no longer any place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
It is precisely the virtual operator's entry into the mobile phone market that brought a marked drop in prices to which the classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, there is no need to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
Moreover, after Mobilking lies the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, they have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world these types of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, are often counterbalanced by the more tight service offer.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap with respect to competition.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland can be a good blow also the bet for a trivial nothing target group.
This operator specifically addresses the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he's the operator he likes and who he can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works for this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether similar concept as that of Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech R. doesn't seem too hopeful.
Rather it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," said in a telephone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the financial group Penta.
Indirectly he said that the current mobile telephone operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest on the launch of a mobile virtual operator already shows the group GTS Novera that would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they'll flash better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with some complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "Until today we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop."
He adds: "On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some specific contract that could be studied in such a short horizon"
Vodafone focuses on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this concerns the sharing of costs and infrastructure.
We regard it as the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition, which would lead to a drop in prices and thereby a fall in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of that is the grab when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the ČTU was at the time of U:fon's entry by the T-Mobile society.
This is attested by the public information available on the ČTÚ websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, the competitive environment in the mobile phone market has not long been open to a fourth operator.
As far as the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would imply for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement was concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
Until today no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for the classic operators," added Kristián Chalupa, from the ÚOHS Department of External Relations, to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices which must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from this, they should note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: " Abroad where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the lowering of prices does not fall within the interest of UNOHS.
The dramatic shock in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clearly the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding rise in responsibility in their market actions.
The tools needed to open up the mobile phone market to virtual operators are, rather, missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," added Chalupa to his response.
Interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many hot spots.
There is clearly an analysis of relevant markets by ČTÚ according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
On this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge is always necessary the agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly in a similar way.
Current complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators there are many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility on ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which ÚOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We've met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was introduced recently to extend ČTÚ's competition in the field of commercial tendering which was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of ÚOHS must know this perfectly, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one's looking.
At the same time, something like a pseudovirtual operator that already exists in Czech mobile networks still goes unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile telephony services which, however, only part of them are public.
These are typically multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile services.
Normally only some chosen ones get the price list from these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same ordering a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited were discovered, it would be possible to talk about breach of contract terms that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given company," Martina Kemrová answered the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above that they can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make a profit that is not negligible and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so they cannot dispose of it as a normal customer of the operators."
This is precisely what should seem to the minimally strange ČTÚ.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile phone operators are blocking their eyes on this type of procedure, why are they blocking the virtual operator's entry?
It is necessary to add that the ÚOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the virtual operator's entry into the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this break-in.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have at the moment intervened and in none of the cases defended the operators but their clients.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to bring up the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge others.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all of this happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators let in any virtual mobile phone operator it will be difficult for the UNOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we will perhaps stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are available four versions - two versions that are Solos, one with male voice and one with female voice, one with Coro and one with instrumentals.
The singing is done by Kateřina Knʹínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose solo singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with the two and then, also, with the Choir to look at the diction so that the text would be well understood, so that it would be consonant," he said.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home played for the first time in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in Josef Kajetán Tyl's original Czech play Fidlovačka and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
