The MHD of Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, it is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company the date when the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can now be purchased by nearly 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously charge it on their chip card at the information centres and stations of the transport company at the stations of the Metro, Muzeum, Mđstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Bonds can already be purchased on the Internet from yesterday on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than 400 people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about ticket sales stalls at metro stations, where until now they had to regularly queue up to take out a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is charged to one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is at the disposal of the passengers a window with prepared personnel that helps the interested with the purchase online and also with the reloading of the voucher purchased on their card," said the project spokesman, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to reload the electronic bonus on the Opencard on the automatic vending machines found in some subway lobbys.
How are these vending machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket chopping machine and the travelers will probably have already noticed them in the subway stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný said.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will only be charged to it.
Electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
In other words, in the ring trains and bus lines from the 300 to 499 numbers used mainly by the inhabitants of the towns of central Bohemia.
"On trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reading card that will help to confirm the validity of the time and the zone of the voucher", explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that sets the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
The ring buses have their reading cards mounted in the driver's locker.
When entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany him with the Opencard in the place destined for it on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the voucher.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drapal said.
Passengers who do not travel on bypass buses and do not remember when it is they end the validity of the voucher can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown the information about the validity of your document.
