Some kids talk at night.
I'm not talking about those who wake up very brightly by telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens you might get scared, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign disorder of sleep called somnilochi.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause to determine its occurrence.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (becoming asleep) or sleepwalking, but it doesn't have to be that way.
As mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever conditions, stress situations or overexcitation.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or quite the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be useful to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any question that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him exit in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress condition).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who find it hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain internal calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the somnilochiae appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not conscious, and you'll break his dream.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes you should consult or find out what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not fall into the temptation of questioning him to extract information from him.
You will get nothing, because being asleep is not conscious enough to organize his thought.
You will also hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even kidding.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts just a few minutes.
