Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan that aims to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
It provides, in particular, for better monitoring by the elected parties of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized by non-payment, and a right to monitor the salaries paid to the leaders of the assisted companies.
U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative on the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a marathon of negotiations that lasted two days.
"We made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current crisis on Wall Street," explained the Democrat.
"It's the fundamental point: if we don't do this, trauma, chaos and disruptions to the daily lives of Americans will be immense," Republican Judd Gregg said.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect of a new failure on the mood of investors.
The last hour they had set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have joined the negotiations late, were more favourable to the agreement, not forgetting to express their discontent at being forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly the one that would allow the owners to keep their home and the one on the salaries of the leaders of the surviving companies by the state.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to congratulate themselves.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
His Republican adversary, John McCain, questioned in another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote on it."
" The important points I read [show] that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said the option of doing nothing is not acceptable."
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the dubious debts, the risky and invindible assets of American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of mortgage risk credits before extending to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and causing a freeze of liquidity and a scrap of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of Republicans elected who had changed the first draft agreement, last week.
We believe that we have come out of the impasse since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only secured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to smooth out the roughness for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that stipulated that if the government had to take losses for five years with this program, it could impose new rates that would seek to help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to which 100 more billion can be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote on the part of Congress.
In exchange for its aid, Washington will get shares in the relief companies that will pay dividends in case of profits and that will be able to resell when the storm will pass.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying the seizure procedures that concerned housing obtained from real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on remuneration and on the cash compensation paid to the leaders of the companies affected by the crisis.
The plan's architects would like to see it put to the vote of the House of Representatives from today and the Senate next Wednesday.
Despite all his efforts, he is still not sure that his plan will be approved.
