What did they produce at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Very soon, on 8 October, criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing frauds of significant damage, in a business way, continuously and in an organized manner in addition to other crimes, including the forgery of documents.
According to the Office of the Prosecutor, they used the funds obtained in the public competitions for their own purposes, often justifying the performance of the tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and that of the municipalities - in total some 65 million HUF - partly stopped in the treasury of the organisation Fiatal Baloldal and partly in the pocket of private persons.
The method, which was also announced by the investigators, was to justify the collection of the funds obtained in the public competitions with false invoices behind which there was no actual execution, the different associations never fulfilled their obligations assumed.
According to the prosecution, most of the invoices were false.
For this purpose, they obtained the cheque books in the Józsefváros District market and the circular stamps were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question that on behalf of which company the forged invoice was to be made was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region to which János Zuschlag sent István Sides.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption and these served as a model for drawing up the invoices they presented, among others, in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labour Affairs, as well as in the City of the Capital.
These invoices were signed mostly by István Sides and his accomplice András đri, who according to our information wrote the necessary reports to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Sides chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic centre provided food for a group of ninety persons from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the center manager - so many people do not fit at the same time in that place.
Similarly, the bill issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
As a hostel in Badacsonytomaj town had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however on the bill there were one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of big fantasy invoice also exaggerated when they pointed to the gastronomic center Pigal Kft. for in the bookkeeping of it - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, informed hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecution and showed him the invoices, he knew that they were false documents.
"On the seal the name of our company and the NIF appeared in the wrong place."
He added: In addition to the formal problems he also did not agree that according to the bill a hundred people were accommodated, since they have only eleven rooms in which there are not so many people.
In addition, meals were also included in the bill, while the restaurant has long been out of operation.
Invoicing enthusiasts were also not informed that the chosen travel agency in Budapest organizes exclusively trips abroad, so that on the cash payment bill they foolishly indicated as service a trip within Hungary, which also did not coincide with the practice of issuing invoices from the agency.
Moreover - as was known during the investigation - VAT was also included in the document, despite the fact that travel outside the territory of the European Union was tax-exempt.
Among other things the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövőért foundation, since the services of that company are not charged with a 25 per cent but only with 15 per cent VAT, in addition the hotel employees only extended machined invoices however the invoice was manual.
In addition the "dispatchers" made other mistakes as well, as in the case of a company in which they put on the invoice as activity carried out the road transport to which - it was known during the investigations of the prosecution - does not realize the company founded as an investment consultant.
Likewise by formal differences - inadequate format of the invoice, false stamp - it was known that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont are false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued such invoices.
Nor did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that when the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation, therefore the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
The invoices were issued knowingly
Another group of false invoice manufacturers are those who were aware that they should issue fictitious invoices.
The Esely Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifju Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about four million HUF on behalf of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of the Collab Kft. - according to the prosecution - was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
In the same way he collaborated with Zuschlag and his accomplices the Biogate Kft., currently under liquidation process, which in 2003 provided invoices worth approximately five million HUF to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, without real economic activity behind.
There was no movement of capital either, as they later cancelled the prepared invoices but forgot to record this entity in their documents.
The following group of fake invoice manufacturers includes those who have some connection with the defendants.
For example, Iván Kubatov was the demander of the Ukrainian manager of the Delta Trio SL with a fictitious headquarters in Budapest, which dealt with the fuel and vehicle trade.
This company issued numerous invoices worth approximately HUF 18 million in October, November and December 2005 on the sale of computer media.
According to the investigation data, these invoices were purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Iván Kubatov should have also dispatched the company-related documents between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov recognized during the investigation that issued invoices for the Atlasz company, for the Hoppa and for Együtt Harmadik Évezredért Alapitvány by charging the amount himself.
The Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and the Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies actually functioned because - according to the defendant - they did not receive work.
But he benefited from these companies, as at the request of his accomplice, lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the company's registration documents, issued invoices on behalf of the companies for the organizations linked to Zuschlag: for Atlasz and for Y-Generáció.
Kubatov on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade gave a total of 15 invoices to various entities worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution found that Kubatov received VAT and 10 per cent of the amount of invoices.
This man even took advantage of the company in commandeer Szi-Beri to issue fictitious invoices used in the contest of Biztos Pont.
The Y-Generació and Szövetség to Modern Magyarországért presented a competition in January 2006 to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility entity of the Socialist Party.
From the contest they obtained 500 thousand HUF respectively, but did not use the money for the objectives of the contest.
To keep this from being discovered, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft were submitted to TMA.
These were the invoices found during the registration of the office that Árpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Some of the defendants will probably report in the trial - as they did in the prosecution - the course of forgery of invoices.
The most interesting thing may be the confession of the defendant János Zuschlag himself, if he decides to dismantle everything.
For his confessions so far have not been very detailed and although he repeatedly promised to talk about everything, this has not been done so far.
The question is: what interest does it have to do?, because perhaps in return for the return of most of the money - fifty million HUF - the Socialists reached an agreement with him so that Zusi will assume all the responsibilities.
Who, on the other hand, for these days could even be offended, since in order to alleviate his prison conditions he applied for house arrest, but was repeatedly denied him.
While the numerous perpetrators of economic crimes of far higher value, who never returned the money, walked freely or at least could wait in their own home for the sentence, he has no chance for that.
Overlay Psychology: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined through the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI).
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, when losing the game the operation of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex intensified.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-prize" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in betting is explained as a prevention in order not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To base their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
In addition, another group was promised that if they win, they will receive $15 more in prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the group members lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one triumph was highlighted and for the other failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For those until now explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so now we come to a third explanation" - established Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
Some 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
A hundred thousand people are estimated to be infected in this country, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humors (sperm, vagina humor, saliva).
Travelers are advised to protect themselves by vaccination against the A and B viruses, against C there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by a general poor condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this, jaundice appears on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, dark-colored urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Annually, one million people worldwide die from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of those infected do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature examination, systematic medical supervision is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoo users.
There are currently some 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptom.
The disease is cured if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so you can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the context of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of studies in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate.
The analysis occurred as follows; they fixed a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the 17th century work of Sassoferrato and the Lady of the Armiño of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers had the hope that the Virgin Mary's spectacle would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
The patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electrical shocks in four successive parts during that period while observing the religious theme painting or the other.
Catholics affirmed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts."
Looking at the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, as for a mother or a father" - said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases of truth changes our personality," Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if Leonardo's Madonna or another painter of his stature were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
