Meanwhile, American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not so their rival, the Microsoft, catalogued by their Windows as conqueror of the World, no matter how much both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for its applications, the code is open and the program package free, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it can also be because geeks see precisely the very problematic relationship between people's rights and the Internet that occurred precisely because of one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: the Web 2.0.
The Web 2.0 is about collaboration, leaving intentional traces behind us and taking advantage of the channels of communication available, and while the measures of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: to show ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them to other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then they can be included in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and they can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
