A written version of the $700 billion bailout package has been prepared and will be implemented in several phases in order to buy bad bank loans.
Half the money will be spent in the first phase.
According to the schedule of the eastern coast during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, the leaders of the congress reached an agreement around the package of financial rescue of 700 billion dollars in total, after several days of discussion - the Reuters has reported.
We have made important progress - said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the North American Congress, stating that it is only necessary to formalize the agreement in a document.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise, said: this program will work and will be efficient but other measures are needed. Pelosi says it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the car of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, i.e. on Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington hours (i.e. before 2 a.m. on Monday, according to Central European hours), without causing a spectacular jump in the bags.
On the bill called the emergency law for economic stabilization of 2008, the first Monday will vote for the American Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
We are happy with the progress made during the night and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy - said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
The program is different from the Bush administration's original proposal to spend all $700 billion to buy bad-quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this amount the Ministry of Finance will buy securities from credit fund, underrated, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This programme will be monitored by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion can be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and securities credit fund securities, as well as other credits of "poisonous" type as well.
The purchase can be made at auctions or directly - reported competent persons of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the financial portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said: the law thus ensures the necessary financial means, which can reach up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the US financial system, be it the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some big financial institutions.
We do everything we need to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it - he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks in distress and waiting for State aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensations, which the American slang simply calls a golden parachute.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and limitations depend on the form of aid from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on the gold parachutes, unless the bank's failed chief retires.
By buying bad loans directly the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the compensations of the bosses are not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations relate only to new contracts to encourage participation in the programme as well.
This is the first case in American history that will be in force a legal limitation on the revenues of the directors general - said Democrat Barney Frank, president of the congressional commission, responsible for the financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since ultimately they will be able to make profits from the transaction as soon as the economy recovers and with it the bank.
According to the bill in the next five years, the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to return to taxpayers the losses of the financial sector.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed reservations about the draft.
This is not what the U.S. citizens entrusted to us, that is, they are not protecting taxpayers' dollars - declared the Republican Congressman of California, Darrell Issa.
His fellow Ohio Democrat, Mary Kaptur, said: the measures were urged by the same ones who are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and declined by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 percent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased by only a minimal measure, with 0.1 per cent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased minimally, with 0.1 percent compared to July.
The biggest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), due primarily to the 4.6 per cent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical industry (1.6 per cent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper manufacture, publishing houses and printing works did not change.
In the rest of the sectors of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a 12-month comparison - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally prices increased by 10.2 percent.
The prices of electricity, gas, heat and water supply exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, prices in the energy sector and in the intermediate sectors remained unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the biggest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
There was a 6.8 per cent decline in consumer goods and 1.4 per cent in investment goods.
Industry export prices calculated at HUF increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decline of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in a month was reduced by 1.7 percent compared to the euro and by 7.1 percent compared to the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent compared to the euro and 15.9 percent compared to the dollar.
