Mp3 Readers Under Accusation, Put Hearing at Risk
Listening to high volume music for a long time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent hearing injuries.
As the European Commission points out, in a statement published in Bruxel it cites the opinion of the Scientific Commission of the emerging and newly identified health risk (Csseri) of the Ue, published today.
"From this scientific opinion – it is read in the note – it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day having the apparatus at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and high acoustic cell phones can unwittingly ruin their ears in an irremediable way," Meglena Kuneva says.
"From scientific evidence – Ue's responsibility follows – a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What counts is to sensitize the consumers and render this information in the public domain.
We must also examine the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are broadly effective and have the passage with the new technology."
Bruxel had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the great use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that caused it.
"Scientists - concludes executive Ue - confirm that it is of concern and the European Commission will now examine together with the Member States and interested parties what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related devices".
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100 dB, but concerns are increasing as the auditory damage that may result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these damage by far by using solutions such as reduced levels and time of exposure to noise.
In his view, the Scientific Committee Ue notes that users of portable musical devices listen to high volume (over 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours a week exceed the current limit for maximum noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
It means that it affects 5-10% of the users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the Ue.
