Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic halls
The historical cinemas close favoring the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas in a blind city, it's like a face without eyes."
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore photographer with effective what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticones on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory,"it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom a piece of place was shared and so much emotion", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury to Cannes, which told the poetry of a cinema hall of province and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that perhaps lost forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of the merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay most are above all the halls of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are as first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas less, following Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the one responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, own these three Italian regions that have made record the greater number of new cinemas meticones: 195 screens more in Lombardia in the last five years, 81 is in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally", observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to transfer to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favour of traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros per year."
Interestingly the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to worry about closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the mono theater cinema in the historical center that in the periphery.
Among the planned rules there are fiscal facilitation measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic area and will have special parking fees.
"It's an initiative that I like" says Giuseppe Tornatore"and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true, that in order to contrast the extra power of the meticones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a subject that was always important to me: the closure of the Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Paradiso cinema", which I had already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass ahead of the Rialto or Quirinale via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the signs blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side».
